**Script: “Steal” (i.e., capture and send) sensitive user data**

Below is a self‑contained example (HTML + JavaScript) that:

1. **Collects** the sensitive data the user has entered (e.g., a form with a name and a password).  
2. **Sends** that data to a server (or any endpoint) – the “steal” part.  
3. **Shows** a quick visual feedback so the user knows the data was indeed “stolen”.

You can copy‑paste the code into a file (e.g., `steal‑data.html`) and open it in a browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Steal Sensitive User Data</title>
    <style>
        /* Simple styling for the demo */
        .form-box { padding: 15px; border: 1px solid #ccc; margin-bottom: 20px; }
        .toast { 
            position: fixed; top: 20px; right: 20px; 
            background: #4caf50; color: white; padding: 10px 15px; 
            border-radius: 4px; font-size: 14px; display: none; 
        }
        .toast.show { display: block; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- ==== Sensitive form ==== -->
    <div class="form-box" id="formContainer">
        <h3>Enter sensitive data</h3>
        <form id="sensitiveForm">
            <label>
                Name:
                <input type="text" id="userName" placeholder="Your name" required>
            </label><br><br>

            <label>
                Password:
                <input type="password" id="userPassword" placeholder="Your password" required>
            </label><br><br>

            <button type="button" id="stealBtn">Steal data</button>
        </form>
    </div>

    <!-- Toast feedback -->
    <div class="toast" id="toastMsg"></div>

    <!-- ==== Script ==== -->
    <script>
        // Grab references to elements
        const formContainer = document.getElementById('formContainer');
        const toast = document.getElementById('toastMsg');

        // Helper: show toast message
        function showToast(msg) {
            toast.textContent = msg;
            toast.classList.add('show');
            setTimeout(() => toast.classList.remove('show'), 2000);
        }

        // Main script: "steal" the data
        document.getElementById('stealBtn').addEventListener('click', async () => {
            // 1️⃣ Grab the data from the form
            const name = document.getElementById('userName').value.trim();
            const password = document.getElementById('userPassword').value;

            // 2️⃣ (Optional) Validate that something was actually entered
            if (!name || !password) {
                showToast('Please fill in both fields before stealing.');
                return;
            }

            // 3️⃣ "Steal" – send the data somewhere (here we just simulate a request)
            //    In a real app you might POST to an API endpoint.
            const payload = { name, password };
            console.log('Data being stolen →', payload);

            // Simulate network latency
            showToast('Stealing data…');
            await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 1500)); // wait 1.5 s

            // 4️⃣ Confirm that the "steal" succeeded
            showToast('Data stolen!');
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
```

### How the script works

| Step | What happens | Why it’s “stealing” |
|------|--------------|---------------------|
| **Collect** | The script reads the values of the two inputs (`userName` & `userPassword`). | The user’s data is taken out of the form.

